Ok, I cannot describe the love I have for this game. You can probably tell this is my favorite game, because of my profile picture. Firstly, there is a massive open world, and you can explore any part of it at any time. The world is very well detailed, with things as small to butterflies to things as big as skyscrapers. Secondly is the vibe this game radiates. It is the most wholesome thing I've ever experienced, while being colorful and, honestly, beautiful at times. Especially the "Wobblies," which are a refreshingly original, yet cute characters. Thirdly, the world feels alive. In some games, the world feels empty and lifeless. Not in this game, There are AI cars, little animals, and so much more that makes this game feel alive. Fourthly, there is an entire "Arcade Mode" which combines parkour, hide and seek, sandbox, and other mini-games that make it amazing.
Also just a quick thing, multiplayer is a little bit laggy if you/the person you are playing with has bad internet.
Lastly, there is just so much to do, from tons of jobs, fun secrets, collecting cars, and so much more. It is so awesome being able to play with friends in the same world, but not have to interact with them, except for seeing them drive by. I wish I could forget this game-just so I could experience it for the first time again. Overall, I so highly recommend this game, everyone should buy it.
-Ari

I absolutely LOVE playing this game with my 5 year old son! Unlike other games out there, this is a simple game that seems truly tailored for all ages. We love driving around, looking for new hidden things to dig up or jumping puzzles to solve. Until recently, my son and I were playing this on PS4, but when I was deployed overseas, this game on steam deck allowed us to continue the fun from afar. Highly recommend for anyone!

Wobbly Life is a truly incredible game. I have been playing this game for years, but it's so fun it still feels like no time has passed since I got the game. Now, I am an achievement hunter at heart, so I like to read through the achievements list and earn everything there. Because of this, I have done a lot of things in Wobbly Life, and I know for a fact that if you like other open-world sandbox games, you will love this game. Don't believe me? Ask the people who made the game (Rubber Band Games). They are actually active in their Discord server, way more than other game creators. But if you're asking me? I say you should get Wobbly Life, and then tell your friends they should get it too!

This game has wonderful graphics and a great story-line along with three other features that i will feature in later sentences.  Wobbly life has created a brand new form of video games, kinda. Well you see there are three main features that i personally, love! First we have JOBS, i think this feature makes wobbly life, wobbly life. I think this allows the game to really feel like its reality which is really cool! secondly, we have MISSIONS, missions are just like jobs except (usually) you get clothes and its something that you can come back to doing. LASTLY, we have RELATABILITY, from being late to work or being laid off wobbly life has many things that make it relatable. (you know, except for a giant slime monster that disposes the garbage and UFO's)

without any of these features wobbly life wouldn't be, wobbly life...

Great for kids.  Appeals to those who enjoy exploration and collecting / completionists.  

As a parent, I definitely recommend.  
-  Community is about as expected: kids -- goofy at times, but overall harmless (i.e. outright griefing is very rare).
-  Communication is limited to emotes and gestures (nothing objectionable).  Players are unable to speak or type directly into the game for communication, so don;t have to worry about stranger danger in that context.  
-  Content can range from super simple to rather complex platforming / parkour (again, consider the target audience).  Just right for kids in the 8-12 range, I would speculate.
-  Zero politics as far as I can tell. 
-  Biggest complaint I can really even think of is that sometimes multiplayer mods will impact my kid's save-game (like money hacks / movement / etc), but nothing harmful.  We can always roll back to a previous save if something is corrupted beyond pbeing able to play the game.  

For example, you'll see many money hacks out there, but money in the game isn't really that big of a deal.  It exists and provides a means to work towards buying something like a pet or a house, but if you have effectively unlimited money, the game is still challenging in other ways.  

There is no competitive advantage, or anything like that.  In fact the game itself is much more oriented towards cooperative gameplay rather than competitive, however there are SOME competitive activities in isolated areas of the game.  

Overall, definitely recommend for kids and parents wanting to spend time with their kids exploring the Wobbly World.

I know I'm not the first to say this but, this game is really not that good. Or at least, in my opinion, it isn't. Sure, it may have some cool art and nice music but, when it comes down to the ACTUAL GAME, it's pretty boring nonetheless. And here is why:

First off, the game is just a collection of mini-games. The so-called "jobs" in this game are just very short mini-games. Which I don't really like playing at all. Especially the newspaper one. And if these jobs are very boring then, why do I do them? It's simple. For money. Money to buy clothes, cars, houses, and pets. Or props if you ever feel like it. And while this may seem good on paper, it really does beg the question. What happens if someone buys everything inside the game? 'Cause I have made $1,000,000 in this and I don't know what to freaking do now. Drive around? What's the point? Do boring jobs? What's the point? Anything I wish to do in this game, I always ask, "What's the point?". Aside from playing online but, that brings me to my next issue.

Online servers are GARBAGE. Total garbage. And there are 2 reasons why. For the 1st reason, the game uses peer-to-peer connection. Yes, peer-to-peer. The main reason why I dislike Deep Rock Galactic. In case y'all don't know, P2P is basically 1 or more people connecting to 1 person's computer (AKA The Host). And while the host gets 0 ping, you can get from 100-300ms ping for no freaking reason, bruh. Doesn't matter how close you are. I would connect to someone who is in the same state as me and yet, I would get 200ms ping. And this can happen if y'all are in the same HOUSE. Like, I know some people out there who can get 200ms ping for connecting to their brother's computer. And they have very fast internet, too like, peer-to-peer servers are very faulty. I'm not gonna lie.

And to make matters worse, the devs added input delay to their servers which makes them even WORSE than before. Like, I would press the move forward key and it would take a full second for my character just to move forward. Making it very hard for me to drive and grab stuff like, what the heck were these devs thinking?

I don't get it, man. Boring game, terrible servers, and a painting that mocks God. How the heck did this game get Overwhelmingly Positive reviews? Oh wait, I know why. It's because most of them are from little kids. That has to be it 'cause, what the FUDGE DUDE???

P.S. I also hate the circular minimap. Zoomed in too close, shows icons that are very far away, and terrible GPS system.

So I was looking for a game that was like GTA but for kids.  Wobbly Life was mentioned in various places, so I looked it up and thought hey, my kids might like this.  My 7 year old has been wanting to play GTA and for obvious reasons, I was not going to allow him to.  So I bought Wobbly Life for all 3 of my boys (9, 7 and 5 years old), and watch them start playing it.  After about 30 minutes of watching them play, I was getting the urge to want to kick one of them off so I could play.  Since I didn't really want to spend another $25 to buy a 4th copy of the game.  But then the older two were leaving the youngest one out, and I thought bugger it, so I bought the game for myself and hung out with my 5 year old while the older ones played together.  After a while we all hung out and explored the map, trying to earn money to buy a house.  After 7 hours, we still haven't bought a house because we have all just been too busy exploring.  My 9 year old loves the axolotl themed stuff he found, so he is happy.

So overall, I definitely recommend this game for younger kids that use a computer reasonably well.  The controls can be a little annoying, but still not rage quitting infuriating (yet). It's a great way for parents to game with their kids too, as I was having heaps of fun just running around with my boys, letting them lead me around, run me over, chase me.  I could hear the breath taking giggles from upstairs.  They loved every second of it, and so did I.  I can't wait to game with them again tomorrow.

So glad I bought this game, even after buying 4 copies at full price.

Love playing this with my younger kids (4-10) in couch-coop (up to 4 players!). It truly is like an SFW version of GTA. Do jobs, buy (or steal) cars, boats, planes and save money for your dream mansion, or that shed in the mountains. The diverse jobs range from simple to complex multi-step jobs that even yield to collaboration with other players. There's a couple biomes to explore, too, and loads of puzzles and races and hidden gems (both figuratively and literally). The physics is a little bit wonky from time to time, and the gfx is fairly simple, but there is a surprising lot of content in there, and new stuff is occassionally added. I wished the game had a little bit more persistence (stuff is reset regularly, i.e. you can't really decorate your homes, and don't even think to leave your lorry full of money parked anywhere, it'll be gone when you return).

If you're a kid or adult aiming to have a fun open world to explore with your children, go for it. 
If you're an adult looking for a challenging open-world, maybe choose something else.

This game *is* fun but when you want to unlock things like pets, the processes involved is just absolute bullshit when one slip can drop something into the water or respawning can set you far enough away that it outright despawns and you have to start the process all over again. (For those inclined, I'm talking about the process of unlocking the ghost pet by acquiring both pearls, which if you fail to get them to the secret area in the mining job before time runs out, both of the pearls also despawn, requiring you to go all the way back to the jungle temple and cave to get them again).

As someone with autism, I just *cannot* fathom the idea of game design where one mistake sets you back to the beginning of a process like that when it could be averted by having a Lost & Found or having objects respawn somewhere safe.

This is seriously one of the best games ever. 
  I bought the game for XBOX because my two young sons love playing it- and I don't trust them to use my computer or laptop alone. But I play it when they aren't playing. Ive been playing Wobbly Life for 3 years now and still haven't done everything there is to do in the game- They keep updating the game adding more jobs, vehicles, outfits, houses, and pets- its crazy.
   I ended up buying the game on my computer too because whenever they do and Update for the game, Xbox only gets access to the updated content a few months after everyone else- so I got tired of waiting basically. What really sucks is that my favorite time of year is Christmas time- and by the time the Christmas update would get to Xbox- I only got to play the Christmas content for a whole 4 days before the removed it. 
  So I'm excited to be playing it on my computer now- even though now I have to go back and basically start from scratch again to get all my vehicles, my pets, outfits, and my mansion back. Its alright though because the game is legit straight fun. Any job you do in the game is fun. I'm super excited about being able to play the new content as soon as its posted now more than anything though!

I tried playing this game shortly after release but after struggling to pick something up off the ground for 10 minutes I quit playing. Dev's said they would address it and I believe they did, but after the recent update I decided to give it another try. I'm now trying to fill ice cream buckets but I failed to meet the time requirements 3 times because of missing the button. Sometimes you get it, sometimes you miss and have to restart. The amount of times you struggle just with basic interactions absolutely kills this game. Another issue, if you're to close to a button, you grab onto the button itself, or whatever its mounted on, instead of actually pushing the button. The game should recognise there is a button/switch there and you should automatically push instead of latching on. When the game constantly does something you're intentionally trying not to do, it just becomes frustrating. I was having fun with some of the games too but it just becomes too frustrating losing due to poor mechanics. 
If they would fix that one issue, I wouldn't really have any other problems with this game. But that one issue is still enough for me to not recommend it. Unfortunately.

Pros:
- This is a silly and fun game. It has loads of little secrets and missions to complete. I would recommend if you want a fun game you can play with a few friends to just mess around in.
- You get rewarded for exploration with little presents or secrets
- You can buy a house with no mortgage
- Money feels like it is going towards something
- Customise your wobbly
- Invincible pets

Cons:
- Some of the platforming is really hard, I struggled with the lazer puzzle due to the wobbliness of my head triggering a lazer.
- The economy makes no sense. The poor housing market :')
- The sleep king stuff needs some kind of fixing! My recommendations: longer time to do the puzzles, perhaps the time starts ticking down when you are in the room rather than including your journey there. Some checkpoints in between puzzles. I know it is probably meant to be challenging but it was frustrating getting all the way to the third puzzle, losing and having to do the first two over and over. 
Maybe some kind of hints? I did see a few people not understanding what they had to do for each puzzle, especially the third room,

Not my cup of tea as a game, but my kids have gone crazy for this game. They obsess over the unlockables, have their friends play multiplayer with them, and just generally talk my ear off about how much they love it. Controls are solid, graphics are nothing too amazing, and it seems to run even on potato PCs. So from that standpoint the devs have done a great job. Quest variety is ok and largely hinges on your ability to complete the game's various odd-jobs. The jobs earn you cash, cash gets pets, outfits, or houses. The kids have love the collection aspect in particular which leads them to scour the game world. The game is growing and still in EA so I expect this content will continue to expand.

As an adult I think your mileage will vary, but Wow has it been a hit with the neighborhood kids.

LOTS OF FUN, BUT ALSO FRUSTRATION. I HAVE PLAYED MORE THAN 100 HOURS AND I MEAN IT FOR REAL.

My kids love it! The game is really COOL to play CASUALLY in coop (allows local split screen):

- wonderfull, silly, violence-free open world
- many jobs to do and puzzles to solve
- unlockable pets, vehicles and suits
- creative nad memorable moments (feeding the monster, hoverboard ride, getting shrunk in the laboratory etc) 
- arcade arena with different games: hide&seek, "Fall guys"-type running, a sandbox mode, conveyor belt game
- supports modding

But after some time of exploring and just casually hanging around, you want to complete tasks, get artefacts, unlock things and earn money to buy cars/houses. Then the frustration kicks in:

- money bags randomly dissapear
- hard-earned artefacts just noclip through the trunk of your car and get lost
- chests are sometimes spawned under the buildings, or the loot slips in the water
- artefacts and gold get stuck under the floor
- some vehicles are almost uncontrollable (airplanes, water scooter)
- airplanes and helicopters randomly explode
- sometimes jobs cannot be done (job target is so far away you cannot complete the job - furniture delivery, fireman...)
- some platforms bounce you off randomly into the water
- fishing is probably the worst minigame I have played in years
- interesting quests like the police job, the temple or secret laboratory are really scarce, 99.5% of the game are just repetitive jobs
- NPCs are scarce, the world is almost empty
- I have been trying real hours to get the randomly generated artifacts like the uranium crystal from the mine or the golden trinket in the trashcan - but unlucky me, they didnt spawn
- at the moment, there is maybe 1 interesting mod available

I understand that most of these are probably early-access bugs, that they appear randomly and not all the time - but they can ruin your gameplay anyway. Imagine playing with your little buddy, thying for half an hour to get an artefact from a cave - and on your way back your helicopter randomly explodes, your artefact gets lost and the little buddy has tears in his eyes...
On the other hand, if you are playing the game coop with your kids that just want to give silly dress to their character, ride the jelly car and bump into everything in their way, then your money is well-spent.

Hey, I might sound negative, but I like the game and it was worth the money. Get it now :)
PS: I am looking forward for the space update!

I have to admit I didn't like the look of this when I first saw it, but as a co-op game I could play with my 6-year old son it seemed pitched at about the right level. I write this not as a review but just as a description of a single event that happened not too long ago. 

Any game can make clumsiness part of its core mechanic. Many do this by just being a bad game; and even those can be unintentionally fun for ten minutes before you scrub it from your disk. Wobbly Life manages to pull of that feat of being actually quite polished and letting the fun emerge from the situations that occur, such as when we took on a seemingly simple ambulance mission...

The patient was up in the mountains. The clock gave us 4 minutes, but we were experienced and we knew the route. This would be a doddle (and I was driving, which was a plus). When I rounded the final corner and saw that the casualty was in the middle of an ice hockey rink, I didn't worry. 3m15s.

"Careful on the ice it's..." He jumps out as I hit the edge and slides ungracefully into the gurney carrying them both to a drift on the far side. Ok. I drive over and brake a bit too sharply, clattering the ambulance into the the pair of them. 3m left..

"You get the doors, I'll load up the..." Cue 30s of us [i]keystone cops[/]ing repeatedly past the patient and the rear doors until one of us finally grabbed hold of him and bundle him into the back. Doors swiftly closed and we were away. 2m15s;  should be a doddle. 

I hit a bump under the snow regaining the road. Not a big deal, but the collision of the back-end with a tree permanently breaks open the back door. 1m50 and I'm going to have to be careful, now.

Back on the road and as I hit the first tight corner a jalopy coming the other way sideswipes us and I bounce over a mound, coming to rest sideways in a funny looking gully, the camera positioned such that I can just catch the gurney sliding out of the back door. Damn. Both of us jump out and look back to see it - and I'm not making this up - disappear at speed around the first corner of a bobsleigh run. "Well, that's still potentially survivable..." I said; "But probably not face-down."

We instinctively jump on the nearby sledge and give chase, all hope of a successful rescue rapidly evaporating. Catching up at the end of the run, we're down to 1m10 and our only hope is to take the "black run". Grabbing an end each of the gurney, we leapt off the side of the mountain, crashing to a halt near a bridge that looked vaguely familiar.

"Wait, I know where we are! Grab that truck!" - My son dutifully "commandeers" a passing pick-up and heads for the bridge, with me gripping its tailgate in one hand and the oddly-passive patient in the other. 30s left and all rules of the road now abandoned we hurtle over the bridge, doing a ton past a petrol station he clips another tree and the whole ensemble carves a graceful parabola through the air, coming to land at...  the foot of the ramp to the hospital!

15s! We can still do this! Our brief celebrations are cut short, however, as I realise that one of us is missing. I right the camera and look up just in time to see the gurney - patient still neatly strapped into it - slide calmly in through the front door of the nearby cinema 100 yards away. 

"Noooooo!" we both shout as the last few seconds tick away. 

"Job Failed."; it says. Maybe, but with both of us corpsing on each others' shoulders, I say Job Done. 

Play this game, but just don't play it alone.

This game is one of the best wobbly physics games I have ever played. This game is definitely worth the £13 that they charge for it! 

The game is so full of life, and there are so many different types of jobs in the game that not a lot of these games actually offer. It's just so creative! 

You can customise your wobbly character in anyway you like, from tops and bottoms to cool hats. You can really be and make yourself in this game anyway that you want! 

There is so much to explore and do. You can buy cool houses, vehicles, compete literally out of this world quests, and more! 

The only thing that I would say that needs to be improved is the online play. The delay time for movement and buttons is quite long (if you are hosting a game, then the delay time shouldn't affect you)! I did measure the delay time once and it was 0.6 seconds! For me, that is quite long. 

Overall, this game is an absolute gem. If you like life games, wobbly physics and cartoony graphics, then their game is definitely for you! Highly recommend!

I might only have five hours in this right now but I can say this is a fantastic game if you want to play a game together with a kid. Honestly I spent hours trying to find good coop type games on Steam that are appropriate for kids and tbh, there are not many kid games in general for PC these days it seems. Well, this game is dead on perfect. It's basically grand theft auto for kids. I am playing with a 6yo girl (first grade) and her family lets her play Cyberpunk 2077 (which oddly, is comparable in an important way), she prefers this game though.

I wish there were more good split screen games for any age but especially appropriate for kids. We are just playing this with an older gaming PC plugged into a TV with two logitech controllers like that really common one that looks a lot like a PS2 controller. The funny thing is, this game is rated exceptionally and I think that is only because there are ten trillion PC games now but literally nobody is trying to make a proper game for kids or that kids and adults can play together. There's nothing special about the game it is just forgiving and silly and generally high quality but it has no competition because nobody else is trying to make games that would compete with this for some reason?

Anyways.. I recommend. It's fun even if just playing as an adult

This game has been so much fun, and STILL is. I await every update, love hearing my brother talk about it, joined their discord, am addicted enough that I am convincing ALL my friends to play. And despite how this review reads, I am a young adult. 

Upon further inspection, I completely agree that this is an epic, indie-game, kid friendly version of GTA. Many comments bring this up, and I thought this before reading those(ran across on accident on reviews last week, have had this game for months/played with my brother at first until I got obsessed). My roommate and I actually have said this jokingly way before I ran across those reviews. It just validated my feelings and hers.

I love all the secret things you can do and unlock, and that there is still MORE coming. This is great for multiplayer, singleplayer(but with friends is best), achievement hunters/goal oriented people like me, to just chill with friends and do stupid fun things/nothing useful too. Ragdolling is fun, etc.

My main point to bring up is during the multiplayer experience, make sure to check that your friend sees what you see on your end when doing tasks/goals/missions/secrets together. As certain progressions don't count for both of you; and it is good to notice at the same moment rather than to have to do a quick redo for another person when it could have been avoided. 

I found when donating to the museum, have your friend and you grab one hand on the object(like a red sparkling gem for example) and walk in together and walk over the yellow circle dropspace. This way you both get credit towards both your sides for the museum. The museum displays based on YOUR progress not everyone's, which is fine, but good to know of--it does not go based on hosts progress either. There are similar rules it seems with quests at times, so just check. I recommend checking with jelly man stuff as well; I will not elaborate cause spoilers--but had to help my Mom redo some stuff since she didn't get same credit.

This game is great for all ages, as I have said, I got this game because of my ten-year-old brother then began to play on my own time alone. And now I am telling my friends to come join me and cause chaos WITH ME. My own roommate and I have started doing stuff together on it quite a bit this last week as well via our steams. 

Overall, if you read this far into this essay-like review, I highly recommend this game for ALL ages and to just explore. Make the most out of it by playing how you prefer; alone, with friends, with wobbly-strangers, family, etc. Steal all the wobbly's cars, do epic jobs, find ALL THE OLD & NEW SECRETS, solve puzzles, ride various vehicles, cause havoc, and just have a good old fun time. Be serious, be funny, work towards goals, and be a yellow wobbly of epicness. This game is worth the 15 dollars and any steam sale price.

Wobbly Life isn't just a silly little game about wobbly people. No, it's so much more than that.

Wobbly Life is an experience, one that gives you a window into a new world, like our own, but better... 

Wobblier...

It is a gripping and exciting tale of labor, capitalism, freedom, success, family, and friendship. Your loved ones will drive you to make a name for yourself, charge forward and push toward your dreams and aspirations. But the world will push back, and you may get knocked down, you may scrape your knees along the way, but it will be worth it. You will stand at the top, and look back on where you didn't give up, and where you kept marching on through rain and snow. You will move on from good to great. From a minivan to a mansion. From pizza delivery to prize winning archaeologist. Every step, every wobble and stumble is a move toward achieving your biggest goals. Wobbly Life is everything, and nothing all at once, and it is exactly what the world needs today.

You will cry, laugh, love, and regret, but you'll enjoy every minute, every wobbly second you spend in your very own

Wobbly Life.

I saw my brother play it with my little nephew, and I said why not try it myself. I played this game with low expectations, Especially since it was made for children. From the first time I played it, I saw the amount of content in it from side missions to main missions. The game is incredibly diverse, especially since it is early access. not a complete game. whatever your age You may like the game. The game does not contain boring childish dialogues or very simple tasks. The game is more like real life. It has jobs that you accomplish for money + houses that you buy + you can buy cars + clothes + animals and other things, you will enjoy it, whether alone or with your friends or brothers

-But there are things that I would like to change or be added,
such as changing the snowy area. Every time I go to it, the graphics seem to change from ultra to very low setting.
Add NPCs walking on the sidewalks
Adding more NPCs in the city to make it more lively
Adding more vehicles and making the car showroom sell special cars for the player and not available in cities
Adding the customization of the house that you buy, whether from the colors of the walls, floors, etc

That's all I have, thank you

Okay, let me tell you about Wobbly Life, the physics-based game that surprised me with its unique approach. It's like a mashup of Human Fall Flat and an open-world sandbox, and boy, does it work brilliantly!

The game's world is vast and content-packed, and the best part is its non-linear design. You can approach puzzles and jobs in so many different ways, it's insane! For example, one time I had to take an object across the map, and the game left it up to me to decide how. The freedom to explore and tackle challenges made Wobbly Life so much more enjoyable than other similar games.

Speaking of challenges, the mini-games and puzzles are a riot! There are 15 different jobs to play, and they're like addictive little treats that reward you with money. From mindless fun to intense puzzles, they've got it all. I couldn't stop myself from returning to them for more.

And can we talk about the physics in this game? It's pure slapstick gold! The way your character moves and stumbles is just hilarious, making every challenge an absolute treat. Whether I was driving, flying, or stumbling around, I couldn't stop laughing.

Oh, and the world itself is a beauty. From mystical jungles to bustling cities and desolate mountains, Wobbly Life's map layout is top-notch. The jobs and quests are perfectly distributed, and there's always something interesting to discover in each area.

Customization is a blast too! You can unlock tons of outfits, and believe me, some of the combinations are downright ridiculous (in a good way!). It's just one of those games that embrace the absurd and make it awesome.

Sure, there are a few minor flaws, like backtracking in some side missions, but they hardly dampened my enthusiasm. Wobbly Life provided me with a sense of freedom I rarely find in other physics-based games, and it was worth every moment.

The graphics are charming and cartoony, reminiscent of The Simpsons or Human Fall Flat. And the music? Fantastic! Each job has its own theme, and they fit the gameplay perfectly. I even caught myself humming along while delivering pizza or flying planes!

Now, multiplayer in Wobbly Life takes the fun to a whole new level. Up to four players can join in the madness, and the jobs and quests adapt beautifully to accommodate more players. Trust me; this game becomes a blast when you're playing with friends!

In conclusion, Wobbly Life is an absolute gem. It takes inspiration from other great games but spins it into something entirely enticing. The mix of exploration, physics-based puzzles, and mindless fun kept me hooked for over 20 hours. So, if you're a fan of physics-based games or just looking for some lighthearted, absurdly enjoyable gameplay, give Wobbly Life a chance. It's a hidden gem that deserves all the love!

The main reason I've been able to sink so may hours into this game is because I play it with my son - some days he wants to collect new items and some days he wants to just mess around and make up games within the world and it's these two factors that make this game a continual comeback for us: collecting new stuff/trophies/vehicles/costumes, discovering new places or easter eggs not noticed before. or:
* making up a story like a bank robbery chase
* hide/seek tag through sections of the world
* jelly hat fights
* one-on-one pretend fights on a high building
* drag racing downtown, 
* hospital (hospital is most exhausting for my dialogue...)
* chefs

All these things are gimicky to an adult but to a kid they are worlds of fun and roleplay.
I wholeheartedly recommend this to those who can use the game in sort of way; outside of that, well it's a discovery and collection quest.

Reminds me of Totally Reliable Delivery Service but it's actually fun to explore and use vehicles rather than just laughing at the bad physic of the characters.

The price is worth it for the number of hours, mostly I just want more content. the islands can feel a little small with how easy it can be to get around but also huge when walking around, that being said I love the planes and would love an island on the scale of GTA San Andreas.

Modding seems to be a recent implementation and if people can extend the wobbly island sandbox, I could see some massive editions being added via modding, would be interesting to see what other jobs people can come up with off the top of my head I can think of Cop, Trucking Delivery Driver, and Tow Truck Driver. Hard to really think of.

Things that I think would be interesting:
1. inventory system, limited to backpacks and storage within your house for saving games, with that.
2. Larger lands, it would be awesome if we could own an airport, even just a single runway to buy planes and have reason to actually use them.
3. Photo mode with a capture system, this could even be a collective system, eg. take pictures of wobbly landmarks, with or without yourself in them.

Games like this will always be about the story the players create, maybe a journal of your adventures with friends would be an interesting option, automatically taking pictures, or adding your own to then be able to look back at what you have done even out of the game.

Awesome game! I like that you can't buy packs of money - everything must be earned. The challenges are fun and the game offers a ton of different elements to play - never boring. I see great potential for financial  education within this game. For example, one could buy investment properties which need upgrading to attract renters to earn money. These properties could have regular fees associated with them for taxes and maintenance and other real-life financial education elements. Such features, I believe, would enable the game to be marketed as a fun financial education game for kids - a feature which, I believe, would generate many more sales. In addition, I'd love to be able to change house interiors and purchase additional furniture. The only frustration I find is with uncovering artefacts. There have been some buried under shipping containers & buildings which are inaccessible and there are far too many dud finds. All in all, a great game with a ton of potential for future growth.

Looking for a game that's equal parts wobbly and wacky? Look no further than Wobbly Life!

This physics-based sandbox game will have you laughing until you cry as you stumble around a world filled with strange characters, absurd situations, and lots and lots of wobbling.

From the moment you start playing, it's clear that this game doesn't take itself too seriously. You'll control a wobbly character that seems to have no bones or muscles, making every movement a comical and unpredictable adventure. Whether you're trying to cross a bridge or climb a tower, you'll be flailing around like a drunken giraffe, and it's impossible not to laugh at your own ridiculousness.

But it's not just your character that's wobbly – the entire world is just as off-kilter. From the wonky buildings to the bouncy cars, everything in Wobbly Life is designed to make you laugh. And with so many different activities to try, from fishing to cooking there's never a dull moment.

One of the best things about Wobbly Life is the multiplayer mode. It's an absolute blast to play with friends, as you stumble and bumble your way through the world together. Whether you're trying to complete a task or just goofing around, the game is always more fun with a group of wobbly pals.

Of course, Wobbly Life isn't perfect. The physics can be a bit wonky at times, and some of the tasks can be a little repetitive. But those minor flaws are easily forgiven when you're having so much fun wobbling around like a goofball.

So if you're looking for a game that will make you laugh, smile, and wobble your way through an absurd world, Wobbly Life is the game for you. It's silly, it's funny, and it's just plain fun – so what are you waiting for? Get wobbling!

This is a good game to play with friends when you want to have fun with no complications. There's no builds to worry about, where everyone is in terms of levels, or initial setup. Instead, you're thrown into this world that is wholesome as hell and just plain fun. A+, do heavily recommend.

This game is not really something I usually play. I only bought it, because it has cute graphics and is non-violent. I wanted something for my 3yr old granddaughter and this game is perfect. She loves it, just running around in the world doing funny stuff. I help her along a bit and realized that the physics is really well done and you can really have some fun with it, So we had some great time together which makes the purchase worthwhile for me, even though it's not my kind of game for me personally.

The game is ridiculously fun with friends, fun alone too but way better co-op. I could go on how much fun it is but theres a few gripes that really need attention.
Air vehicle health is almost non existent, touch basically anything, land a chopper anything but perfect and it explodes instantly launching any cargo you have who knows where. Planes are essentially same.

Air control isnt bad but the camera angles get funky, because "look" is your control you cant look around. 


 Lost items dont respawn, so if you get a item that needs to be turned in and lose it "happens very easily" You either have to restart the game or move on until later.
Earnings are too low on missions. Theres probably 15 or so different jobs to earn money and most only pay 30 to 40 dollars . Ive done every mission multiple times and I'm still at 7k with cool houses costing 11k alone the game is already feeling VERY grindy . Considering this is a casual style game, thats way too much work just to open more fun in the game. 

Arcade mode just dropped so I'm hoping that makes a bit of cash too because spending 5 minutes to do a job over and over for 30 bucks isnt fun. The jobs generally are really fun, but the reward is so low it actually takes away from casual goofing off and enjoyment while everyone keeps grinding to get a car, outfit, pet ect.

For it's single player [i]I can recommend the game[/i], as for the multiplayer I simply cannot in it's current state. I bought this game to play with my fiance but it completely unplayable no matter who the host is. Our internet is good and we live under the same roof so we should have no issues as we play other more demanding games with no issues that run under P2P (peer to peer) connections, after doing research on Reddit and Wobbly Life's Discord I found the problem lies in how the developers handle lag (which is adding a internal delay to your input in multiplayer to prevent stutters) but all this does is create massive delays in your input i'm talking +5 seconds and if it gets really out of hand you can see yourself stuck floating somewhere while the host sees you running off into the middle of nowhere and then you finally catchup after two minutes. This type of delay is unplayable because most of the "jobs" in Wobbly Life require you to use your reflexes and you physically cannot do that with an input delay.

I really hate having to give a game like this a negative review, I can see it's potential and I can see it's charm but as it stands this is a [b] buyer beware review [/b]as I've read numerous discussions of people falling into the same problem as myself and the developers have acknowledged this issue but it seems they refuse to look further or for a solution (I'm certain a dedicated server would fix this but they don't support that currently)

This game beats the pants off Roblox and it's monetization.  If you want a game you can play offline with your kids, with way more content than a Roblox server, but isn't Minecraft, this is the game.

Heads up however: this is a make your own fun game.  While there is a surprising amount of content hidden all over the world (from subterranean Indiana Jones type adventures, to a science lab where you play a version of Honey I Shrunk The Kids), you will have trouble finding it in this large open world with mostly nothing in it.  I believe the developer will add more content over time, and the game's heart is solidly in the right place.  But, as an adult playing with a kid, be prepared to let their imagination guide the play.  There's more 'game' here for roleplaying and goofing around than for actual challenge and gameplay.  That said it's an amazing value.

We figured we would give it a try and if it's horribly broken we'd just refund it. All this preamble to say we went into playing this game with very low expectations and high standards.

My friends and I are now approaching the 50 hour mark of the game and we've just about completed all the achievements, trust me when I say that this game seems like a very shallow and simple game but that is hiding a deep exploration driven sandbox that has an unexpected amount of stuff to discover! We absolutely love Wobbly Life!

This game hits a certain stride with me, as if I have truly been wanting to live a small town life all this time, enjoying outings with those I have grown up with and know better than any scientist knows their subject. Wobbly Life is still in early access, and so there are clearly some missing features and times when the game can feel under-populated, but for its release date being slated over a year away, there is already plenty of content within the game to satisfy a single person, and with friends, it seems as those it will never cease to have something to do. One has to go into the game expecting it to be the experience that it looks like; it is not GTA and hopefully never will be. The only bugs I have found so far are ones with the player icons while in an online game, and the general distastefulness of the icons themselves. I do have one gripe, though, and that is with the difficulty of fishing. I spent at least seven minutes trying to reel in a tuna. I made a little poem about it: Great Tuna of mine; Seven minutes on my line; Found you, but lost mind. And then once I sold the fish, the cash fell into the water, and I got nothing for my strenuous efforts: A tranquil marketplace, Full of the scends where its wares are bore. A happy-go lad, Nearly tripping over himself to sell his score. The deal made, But a fatal error as well. The lad swears to heaven and hell; He rues the day. A forlorn lad goes out to fish some more.

While I was at my families for a fortnight, my sister (who is only a year younger than me) wanted to play some video games with me, but only equipped with a Steam Deck, every game either didn't do split-screen, or wasn't her cup of tea.

I came across this game while looking through my queue and bought it, expecting to play for about 20 minutes, then refund it. This didn't happen.

Instead, we spent a large portion of the game just making our own scenarios, messing around with the vehicles, and exploring was really fun (and sometimes, even rewarding!). 

Even her friend, who doesn't enjoy games, had a blast playing 3-player split screen. It's a fun title, and I'm really looking forward to the new content this game releases. My only gripe is that split-screen on Steam Deck was very choppy, but was still a great experience, it was reminiscent of the N64 GoldenEye days.

I'm returning home during Easter, and my sister is looking forward to playing Wobbly Life again.

Thanks RubberBandGames for this wonderful experience :)

Never laughed so hard playing a game with friends in my life. Jackbox didn't even compare to this. 

I HIGHLY recommend doing this with friends for your first time if possible. Stumbling around messing with the physics engine and trying to figure out how to do all the little jobs brings out a sense of hilarity I never thought possible. 

I couldn't breathe as we spent an hour chasing the train around the map trying to have it hit various things (or trying to hit various things with our vehicles to see how far they'd go). The ability to hold on to the wings/body as one friend takes off in a little bi-plane/helicopter (and daisy-chain the rest of your friends in a hand-holding physics nightmare) was some of the funniest shit I've ever seen. Try holding on to the propeller of the helicopter for extra credit.

Fumbling around failing at all the jobs, then the chaos of trying to load all your money (yes the money is an object too) into a truck to take it to the ATM and sort out whose was whose in the crazy scramble to deposit it so you can afford a little house or that hilarious hat you're trying to buy (if it gets to be too much, I recommend everyone uses their own vehicle for money transport... but where's the fun in that, eh?) was some of the most chaotically funny fighting I've ever had with my friends. 

Great for a good bit of humor, we haven't played much recently, but every now and then we get the itch to hop on and just mess around and laugh for a few hours. 

I'm sure the game is adorable and endearing on its own, but definitely 10000% better with friends.

The Simpsons Hit & Run meets Goat Simulator.

It's lacking a lot of features to keep it interesting, but that's because you're supposed to bring along your friends and build your own fun. The world feels empty and hollow because it lacks NPCs going about their business. There are a few people driving vehicles that you can see from time to time, but nowhere near enough to convince me that this world is truly lived in.
You sadly cannot mix hairstyles with hats, so you could either have a gnome beard or a gnome hat, but never both at once. How am I supposed to fulfil my gnome roleplay fantasies if I can't be bearded with a pointy hat? It's outrageous. I'd also like to see more options for customisation in the future.

The characters with dialogue are all 2 dimensional and zany, which makes them kind of samey.

The very good sandbox/adventure game.

You can ride vehicles, do jobs (each with its own mechanics and one or other unlock), catch fish, search for treasure, and complete occasional larger quests.

The game looks good, and sounds good, and plays good, and online multiplayer works really well, even across large distances. As a game with vehicles and moving parts, you occasionally get Certified Physics Moments, but you don't usually lose much progress as any lost important items respawn where you found them.

All in all it's a delight - I feel like the primary potential for improvement here is making it easier to figure out what you haven't seen yet when coming back to the game after a few updates.

I have been playing this game for a few weeks now, and i have to say, its one of the most entertaining games i have ever played. Whether um driving cars, flying planes, or completing mini games, there is always something new to discover. Whether you are playing alone or with friends, this game is sure to keep you entertained for hours on end.

So what happens when you take the ragdoll and grab physics of Human Fall Flat and drop them into a open-world adventure with no real goal except to have fun just flailing about and creating chaos? You get Wobbly Life. I'll admit that I had actually never heard of this game until I saw a certain group of Youtubers fooling around with it and that got me interested in looking at what the game had to offer. When I actually picked it up and played it, it's safe to say I wasn't disappointed.

The open world here is surprisingly-big for what you would tend to expect from a game like this. The game is, so far, split up into a selection of around half a dozen islands, each with their own selection of things to do, jobs to earn money with and unlockables. Want to go to the mine and dig up some ore in exchange for cash in the island up north? Want to go to a disco club on the main island and make some money in a rhythm game? Want to just forego the money and go exploring the nearby tropical island to see if there's any mysteries there you can unlock cool stuff with? You're free to do whatever you want whenever you want it. The only goal you have when you start the game is to afford a place of your own, and after that you're just left to your own devices. This game is super easygoing on how you progress and it actually rewards curious and explorative players with special unlockable goodies like unique vehicles, clothing and pets.

Additionally, I'm surprised at the level of puzzle-solving there is in this game due to it clearly being a game that gamers of all ages can pick up and play. A lot of the things in this game are easy enough to figure out but unlocking some of the special cars, clothing and pets requires a surprising amount of steps with very little hints or clues. I won't give any specific examples here just for the sake of potentially spoiling a cool reward for someone who hasn't unlocked it yet but a couple of unlocks require you to do something while in the process of doing a specific job or in the middle of a timed race. Personally I really like that because the game goes out of the way to reward people who like to explore.

Now, I should also bring this up: This game was very-clearly made with multiplayer in mind. The game is perfectly playable and fun if you're playing on your own but there are a handful of jobs in the game that are a royal pain to do without a couple extra sets of hands helping you. For me, the newspaper and ice cream jobs are especially annoying to try and do on my own and you need to be near-perfect with how you play either of those games if you're solo and still want to pass the jobs. Like I said, I know that the games were made to be fun for more than one player but, since I've only played solo so far, the only thing those jobs have brought me thus far is just headaches.

I definitely recommend this game, especially if you're the type that likes to explore at your own pace or if you're looking for some mindless fun you can have with a few friends. I wasn't expecting the game to be as fun as it is when I picked it up, and I think it exceeded my expectations greatly considering the Youtubers that introduced me to the game didn't actually do much with it now that I see what the game has to offer. Now I'm looking forward to seeing what the devs do next with it and what they do to add to the game when there's already quite a bit to do here.

This is a great game for the kids to play. Unfortunately for younger children (age 5 and 7 in my case) the jobs are too difficult. I would really like to see the following improvements:

1. Fix multiple controllers being able to interact with another player's start menu. If one person pauses the game, people already playing will of course change the menu button and might even click gamepad button A and has many times caused someone to leave the game or respawn.

2. Add the ability to turn off or extend time limits for jobs. The kids want to do jobs like taxi driver and delivering pizzas, but the time limits are so harsh that I even have a hard time with them. I still haven't completed the mail delivery job. It is very sad to see them trying their best and getting a "JOB FAILED" with no money for the work they did. Almost worth changing to a thumbs down, seriously.

3. Fix the minimap for split screen clients - they see every waypoint so it's very cluttered. Player 1 is OK although it's still dumb the stars show up at all times. If I want to go to a star I can mark it on my map. Less clutter please.

4. Fix split screen text not scaling sometimes, making text extraordinarily hard to read on a TV. most is ok, but some I have to stand up next to the screen to read.

5. Fix GPS navigation it's awful. It often suggests an unnecessary road and likes to flicker rapidly between two or three different routes. I have made many wrong turns because of the bad gps.

6. Add swimming. Drowning is done really poorly. It's probably the worst drowning system of any game I've played.

7. Let me raise the view distance or make it unlimited.

Wobbly Life is a sandbox game developed by RubberBandGames and published by Take-Two Interactive. The game is set in a colorful and whimsical world where players can explore, interact with various characters, and complete tasks to earn rewards.

One of the standout features of Wobbly Life is its emphasis on humor and wackiness. The game is full of quirky characters and bizarre scenarios, making it a fun and lighthearted experience. Players can customize their characters with various outfits and accessories, adding to the game's humorous and playful tone.

In terms of gameplay, Wobbly Life offers a variety of activities and tasks for players to complete. These include fishing, cooking, driving, and a ton more. Completing these tasks earns players money, which they can use to buy new items for their character.

The game also offers multiplayer mode, allowing players to team up with friends and explore the world together. The multiplayer mode adds an extra layer of fun and social interaction to the game, making it a great option for groups of friends looking for a casual and entertaining gaming experience.

Overall, Wobbly Life is a fun and lighthearted game with plenty of humor and charm. It's a great option for players who enjoy comedic games and are looking for a laid-back and enjoyable experience. However, it may not be the best choice for players looking for a more serious or complex game.

Looked fun and promising, but missed many marks. The first issue is game slowdown; the more local players you add, the slower the game runs (but time remains consistent). This makes doing job downright impossible as the timer runs out way too soon, which leads me to my next point. Even when playing solo the job timers are RIDICULOUSLY short. I was able to complete the tutorial job (as it has no timer), but not any of the 5 others I tried in game. Are you suppose to do the job *flawlessly* and anything short is a fail? The next issue is the minimap showing FAR away jobs - like insanely far away. You're gonna be walking a long time before you get to it, and probably pass many others along the way. Sure you can use the world map to find the closest jobs, but even that is a chore as its difficult to determine your heading. The final issue the world map not showing job objectives; the only way you know where to do is by following a very confusing arrow in-world, which since you don't know WHERE it actually is, your only hope is to drive straight at it, over mountains, across waters, though obstacles, etc. I feel like this can't possibly be right and don't understand how this game has this many positive reviews. The UI is severely under-polished and barely functional, enough to make me regret wasting my time with this game.

[b]Wobbly Life[/b] is a jolly early-access, open-world physics sandbox that can be played solo, or in online or local co-op! Players will take on jobs, discover mini-games and quests and explore a whole wide wobbly world.

It is full of wonderful silliness and has the potential to provide multiple hours of fun with lots of varied content and things to do. The cute aesthetic and sound design are adorable and work perfectly with the wobbly ragdoll physics and jovial tasks. While the game has a casual feel overall, there is plenty going on and there is a nice level of challenge across the various activities to make sure things stay interesting. Wobbly Life is a pleasure to play and is great value for money with regular updates and I happily recommend this game to players of all ages!

This game has and endless amount of hours of content. Even though the game is cheap, the developers of the game have spent an insane amount of attention to detail on the game. There is so much to explore, to do and to enjoy that I can not even comprehend that this game is made by such a small studio. 

The gameplay itself is wonky but fun and keeps the game alive. What makes the game so beautiful is the small things. The game offers so much in order of gameplay ranging from different vehicles handling better according to their price, to different clothing that changes the way things around you act. Some NPC's will even get mad and follow you around if you hit their car. The level design is incredible, there is so much to explore and see throughout the whole map and its made in a way that you think to yourself "why would the developers put this here when they know that 90% of the playerbase wont even see this".  Things like this make this game great, hopefully with future updates they add even more things as the possibilities are literally limitless to what they can add to the game.

It's a cute game. I think it has a lot of potential. The game seems to be at a very raw state. I have not encountered any glitching or lag. It is just a little lack luster at the moment. There needs to be more people in the world and more jobs. I am a little confused why there is absolutely no inventory system or maybe a backpack...something. Dragging bags of money in to trucks and trying to drive a truck down a mountain without loosing money is annoying and difficult. I also don't understand why we can buy things like a tv or food when you have no reason to have them and (unless you buy a house) no where to put them, and even then when you buy a home you cannot place things nicely. 
Yes I still think it is a fun and very lighthearted, casual game. I just crave more from it. There is endless potential here and I really hope the devs create more for us!

-Wobbly Life- is a game you play if you want to enjoy yourself and just have something fun to do.  You can play solo and online.  Online you can have a maximum of 4 people on a server, which I thought was a bit bad when the map is so big and there is so much to explore.  But many on the servers often find all 4 together, so if there were many, it might also be a bit much for the individual player.  In the game, it's all about getting cool houses, outfits and cars.  You get money for all the different jobs such as farmer, cook, ambulance driver, ice cream maker and a lot of other things.  The developers also make frequent updates so that you can play, play and play the game for a long time.

I truly enjoy playing this game! I can never get bored! 

However there are some issues I ran into, although they are nothing major. There is a glitch in the construction job with the left conveyor where it the wood will start to shake and you won't be able to slice it. Although, if you go to the map, this usually fixes itself. It can merely be annoying sometimes.

Something I would like to recommend is that there should be an option to respawn your furniture if it is knocked over. (It's also way too easy to knock over) If someone messes with your furniture, it can be annoying trying to get it back into place. 

Otherwise, this game is amazing. There is so much to do and it's always fun and exciting. 10/10 would recommend!! <3

Amazing game with great developers!
Fantastic game to play with your kids from the couch.
Fun for adults and kids of all ages.
My wife loved it so much, she got her own copy for her own Steam account so she could play on her own in addition to playing with the rest of us.
Biggest limitations are probably:
- The 4 player maximum, which is fine for split screen anyway, since more than that would be difficult on a single screen.
- No modding yet. (This would be a very fun game to mod for.)

Would recommend, especially if you have kids!
